1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,900
 If this is the first time you come to this series,

2
00:00:02,900 --> 00:00:05,600
 this is actually the last lecture we have,

3
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:06,800
 but we still welcome you,

4
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:08,880
 whether this is your first time or this is,

5
00:00:08,880 --> 00:00:12,140
 you know, you are with us during the four lectures.

6
00:00:12,140 --> 00:00:15,560
 We are very fortunate to have four different,

7
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:19,820
 distinguished scholars from different parts of the world

8
00:00:19,820 --> 00:00:21,440
 to speak to us.

9
00:00:21,440 --> 00:00:23,320
 And tonight, the last session,

10
00:00:23,320 --> 00:00:28,320
 we are going to have Dr. Rula Kuri-Manshu.

11
00:00:29,560 --> 00:00:31,560
 I think I'll just say it one time, okay?

12
00:00:31,560 --> 00:00:33,720
 (audience laughing)

13
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:37,840
 To speak to us, okay?

14
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:39,400
 Before introducing Dr. Rula,

15
00:00:39,400 --> 00:00:42,440
 I'd just like to tell you, in case you don't know,

16
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:47,240
 that this lecture is supported by Josephine Soh Fund,

17
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:48,640
 Memorial Fund.

18
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:53,640
 Josephine Soh is a very influential Christian leader

19
00:00:53,640 --> 00:00:55,700
 of the last generation.

20
00:00:55,700 --> 00:00:59,040
 She founded the Breakthrough Organization

21
00:00:59,040 --> 00:01:01,440
 and the Breakthrough Magazine.

22
00:01:01,440 --> 00:01:04,720
 She also founded Breakthrough Magazine in 1973,

23
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:07,320
 and it has influenced a whole generation

24
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:10,520
 of Christians in Hong Kong, including me.

25
00:01:10,520 --> 00:01:13,040
 I remember reading the Breakthrough Magazine

26
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:14,880
 when I was in high school.

27
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:18,960
 I wasn't a Christian then, but I was so impressed

28
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:22,640
 by how they talk about Hong Kong culture

29
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:26,760
 with a kind of seriousness and with a kind of warmth.

30
00:01:26,760 --> 00:01:30,960
 It showed me the Christian faith is really a faith

31
00:01:30,960 --> 00:01:33,480
 that is into the world.

32
00:01:33,480 --> 00:01:35,760
 It's not something that is out of the world.

33
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:40,600
 It is really involved with the life, real life of people.

34
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:44,200
 So we are so glad that we have four speakers

35
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:47,760
 that have lots of experience of how to practice life,

36
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:49,800
 practice faith in real life.

37
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:53,600
 Tonight's speaker is Dr. Rula.

38
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:56,360
 She is the founder and director

39
00:01:56,360 --> 00:02:00,320
 of Nazareth Center for Peace Studies.

40
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:05,320
 So she has experience working for peace in Israel,

41
00:02:05,320 --> 00:02:08,800
 the land of Palestine.

42
00:02:08,800 --> 00:02:13,360
 As we know, this is a place full of conflicts,

43
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:17,280
 and Dr. Rula, as a Palestinian, as a Christian,

44
00:02:17,280 --> 00:02:20,640
 and as a woman, is triple minority.

45
00:02:20,640 --> 00:02:24,480
 And I'm sure she has lots of experience to share with us

46
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:29,480
 how she can advocate or promote peace in such a setting.

47
00:02:29,480 --> 00:02:35,920
 And the responder tonight is Dr. Winnie Fung.

48
00:02:35,920 --> 00:02:39,160
 She is the chief executive of Cedar Fund.

49
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:42,720
 She was also associate professor of economics

50
00:02:42,720 --> 00:02:44,240
 at Whitten College.

51
00:02:44,240 --> 00:02:47,080
 She got a PhD in developmental economics

52
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:48,920
 from Harvard University.

53
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:50,480
 I'll tell you a secret.

54
00:02:50,480 --> 00:02:52,520
 When I was an undergrad student,

55
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:55,960
 I applied for a PhD in economics in Harvard,

56
00:02:55,960 --> 00:02:57,560
 and I got rejected.

57
00:02:57,560 --> 00:02:59,120
 (audience laughing)

58
00:02:59,120 --> 00:03:04,120
 So obviously, Winnie is a much smarter person than I am.

59
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:07,800
 Okay, before much ado,

60
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:12,800
 I would like to invite Dr. Rula to come up to the podium.

61
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:15,760
 Okay.

62
00:03:15,760 --> 00:03:18,840
 (audience applauding)

63
00:03:18,840 --> 00:03:21,080
 (coughing)

64
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:41,880
 - Good evening.

65
00:03:41,880 --> 00:03:46,720
 It is such a pleasure to be with you today.

66
00:03:48,600 --> 00:03:53,600
 It's a pleasure to take part in the CGST

67
00:03:53,600 --> 00:03:59,240
 50 years celebration.

68
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:02,040
 I'm happy to be with you today,

69
00:04:02,040 --> 00:04:04,420
 and I bring you greetings from Nazareth,

70
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:06,280
 the hometown of Jesus.

71
00:04:06,280 --> 00:04:09,080
 I bring you greetings from Nazareth Center for Peace Studies.

72
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:14,080
 It's the center where we do peace building

73
00:04:14,080 --> 00:04:16,600
 in a land torn by conflict.

74
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:19,160
 And I bring you greetings also from Nazareth

75
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:20,480
 Evangelical College.

76
00:04:20,480 --> 00:04:22,840
 This is where I also work part-time

77
00:04:22,840 --> 00:04:28,060
 as a professor in Christian ethics and reconciliation.

78
00:04:28,060 --> 00:04:39,920
 Have you seen this drawing before?

79
00:04:39,920 --> 00:04:42,640
 No.

80
00:04:42,640 --> 00:04:43,560
 Okay.

81
00:04:43,560 --> 00:04:47,920
 So this drawing went viral last year.

82
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:49,080
 It was on Facebook.

83
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:50,800
 It went viral.

84
00:04:50,800 --> 00:04:52,460
 And I will tell you why.

85
00:04:52,460 --> 00:04:58,640
 This drawing is by a little girl,

86
00:04:58,640 --> 00:05:04,320
 13 years old, called Anja Rosen.

87
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:07,180
 She is from Slovenia.

88
00:05:07,180 --> 00:05:13,160
 She was chosen from 600,000 children around the world

89
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:16,880
 in a competition to create a piece of art

90
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:21,220
 that show what peace look like.

91
00:05:21,220 --> 00:05:26,480
 She said,

92
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:33,320
 humans are woven together.

93
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:36,220
 If someone gives up, others fall.

94
00:05:36,220 --> 00:05:42,160
 We are all connected to our planet and to each other,

95
00:05:42,680 --> 00:05:45,160
 but we are little aware of it.

96
00:05:45,160 --> 00:05:47,720
 We are woven together.

97
00:05:47,720 --> 00:05:52,240
 Other people we weave alongside my own story

98
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:54,420
 and I weave theirs.

99
00:05:54,420 --> 00:06:02,560
 This photo actually summarize my lecture today.

100
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:07,020
 But I will take this further

101
00:06:07,020 --> 00:06:10,480
 and add to it some discussion

102
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:14,760
 about from a theological and cultural perspective.

103
00:06:14,760 --> 00:06:21,840
 In a world characterized by diversity,

104
00:06:21,840 --> 00:06:25,040
 division, and violence,

105
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:28,640
 and following the devastation of October 7 war,

106
00:06:28,640 --> 00:06:33,640
 the pursuit of peace remain a big challenge,

107
00:06:33,640 --> 00:06:35,600
 even a distance dream.

108
00:06:36,920 --> 00:06:40,960
 Achieving peace often involves exploring the depth

109
00:06:40,960 --> 00:06:45,660
 of our identities and understanding the complex relationship

110
00:06:45,660 --> 00:06:48,300
 between personal and communal narratives.

111
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:52,960
 This journey is especially meaningful

112
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:54,800
 within theological framework

113
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:57,480
 across diverse cultural context.

114
00:06:57,480 --> 00:07:02,480
 How should we view our identities?

115
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:07,160
 How should we relate to the other?

116
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:11,360
 How should we make peace with the other?

117
00:07:11,360 --> 00:07:18,200
 Four different cultural and theological perspective

118
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:23,880
 embrace theology,

119
00:07:23,880 --> 00:07:30,280
 Ubuntu, Sulha, and Gwanshi provide unique

120
00:07:30,280 --> 00:07:33,780
 and insightful approach to these timeless questions.

121
00:07:34,780 --> 00:07:39,780
 Rooted in Western, South African, Middle Eastern,

122
00:07:39,780 --> 00:07:44,660
 and East Asian traditions,

123
00:07:44,660 --> 00:07:46,980
 this perspective over a rich framework

124
00:07:46,980 --> 00:07:48,700
 for understanding peace.

125
00:07:48,700 --> 00:07:54,220
 In this discussion, I will explore these cultural theologies,

126
00:07:54,220 --> 00:07:56,260
 compare their insights,

127
00:07:56,260 --> 00:07:59,480
 and suggest practical ways to nurture peace.

128
00:08:03,240 --> 00:08:06,860
 Finally, I will reflect on how these perspective

129
00:08:06,860 --> 00:08:09,980
 deepen Christian theology of reconciliation.

130
00:08:09,980 --> 00:08:15,300
 Embrace theology.

131
00:08:15,300 --> 00:08:18,780
 In his book, "Exclusion and Embrace,"

132
00:08:18,780 --> 00:08:22,340
 Merus Labwolf argues that the expanding conflict

133
00:08:22,340 --> 00:08:25,820
 between cultures are part of a larger problem

134
00:08:25,820 --> 00:08:28,300
 of identity and otherness.

135
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:35,840
 He addressed the sacralization of cultural identity

136
00:08:35,840 --> 00:08:41,400
 and warn against a blind self-righteousness,

137
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:43,920
 particularly when cultures prioritize

138
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:46,900
 their cultural identity over their faith.

139
00:08:46,900 --> 00:08:52,800
 He argues that this misalignment prevent Christian

140
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:56,520
 from acting on the gospel call of reconciliation.

141
00:08:59,800 --> 00:09:03,580
 To counter this, he proposed a balanced relationship

142
00:09:03,580 --> 00:09:07,420
 between distance from the culture and belonging to it.

143
00:09:07,420 --> 00:09:10,820
 He suggest that Christians should distance themselves

144
00:09:10,820 --> 00:09:14,500
 somewhat from their culture and prioritize loyalty

145
00:09:14,500 --> 00:09:16,940
 to the God of all cultures.

146
00:09:16,940 --> 00:09:21,860
 Positioning themselves with one foot in their culture,

147
00:09:21,860 --> 00:09:23,880
 as I mentioned yesterday,

148
00:09:23,880 --> 00:09:28,160
 and one foot and the other foot in God's future.

149
00:09:29,380 --> 00:09:32,460
 This balance allow for both allowing space

150
00:09:32,460 --> 00:09:37,460
 for accepting the other, as well as judging ourselves

151
00:09:37,460 --> 00:09:40,920
 in light of God's ultimate reality.

152
00:09:40,920 --> 00:09:45,660
 To maintain cultural uniqueness

153
00:09:45,660 --> 00:09:48,300
 while pursuing universality,

154
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:53,300
 Wolf draws from Paul teaching on unity.

155
00:09:53,300 --> 00:09:57,620
 Neither Jew nor Greek, slave or free,

156
00:09:57,620 --> 00:10:01,840
 male or female, for you are all one in Christ.

157
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:09,100
 The Pauline move is from separated bodies

158
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:11,900
 to the community of interrelated bodies.

159
00:10:11,900 --> 00:10:16,040
 The one body with many discrete members.

160
00:10:16,040 --> 00:10:21,740
 He emphasized the need for both distance and belonging,

161
00:10:21,740 --> 00:10:25,820
 arguing that belonging without distance destroys

162
00:10:26,660 --> 00:10:31,660
 while distance without belonging isolates our identity.

163
00:10:31,660 --> 00:10:38,380
 He employs differentiation to describe the activity

164
00:10:38,380 --> 00:10:42,480
 of separating and binding,

165
00:10:42,480 --> 00:10:45,400
 which foster patterns of interdependence.

166
00:10:45,400 --> 00:10:49,980
 Identity emerged from both distinction from others

167
00:10:49,980 --> 00:10:53,760
 and internalization of relationship with others.

168
00:10:54,860 --> 00:10:56,740
 We define ourselves not solely

169
00:10:56,740 --> 00:10:58,740
 by being distinct from the other,

170
00:10:58,740 --> 00:11:03,340
 but by being distinct yet interconnected.

171
00:11:03,340 --> 00:11:06,140
 So we are different but are connected.

172
00:11:06,140 --> 00:11:09,780
 We can't isolate ourselves from the other.

173
00:11:09,780 --> 00:11:12,980
 Attempt to exclude the other from our identity

174
00:11:12,980 --> 00:11:15,420
 lead to losing ourselves.

175
00:11:15,420 --> 00:11:21,240
 Differentiation is the complex process

176
00:11:21,240 --> 00:11:24,420
 by which the self and the other negotiate their identity

177
00:11:24,420 --> 00:11:27,400
 in a mutual interaction.

178
00:11:27,400 --> 00:11:32,360
 A skillful balance of inclusion and exclusion.

179
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:38,920
 According to this identity definition,

180
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:42,140
 Wolf conclude that both cutting off,

181
00:11:42,140 --> 00:11:45,700
 both cutting off the bonds

182
00:11:45,700 --> 00:11:50,420
 and removing separation lead to exclusion.

183
00:11:53,060 --> 00:11:54,980
 So what is exclusion?

184
00:11:54,980 --> 00:11:58,560
 Exclusion happens when identity is constructed

185
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:00,720
 as pure without the other.

186
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:06,740
 Here we are on our side, the good and the innocent,

187
00:12:06,740 --> 00:12:11,600
 and there on the other side, the guilty and the evil.

188
00:12:11,600 --> 00:12:17,380
 Exclusion replace mutual giving and receiving

189
00:12:17,380 --> 00:12:22,220
 with violence, assimilation, abandonment, and more.

190
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:27,820
 Wolf asserts an identity,

191
00:12:27,820 --> 00:12:29,980
 so we are speaking about identity,

192
00:12:29,980 --> 00:12:34,500
 identity capable of making peace is a centered self

193
00:12:34,500 --> 00:12:39,260
 as exemplified by Paul in Galatians 2.20.

194
00:12:39,260 --> 00:12:41,900
 I have been crucified with Christ.

195
00:12:41,900 --> 00:12:45,760
 I no longer live, but Christ live in me.

196
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:50,820
 This self must undergo de-centering

197
00:12:50,820 --> 00:12:54,640
 by identifying with the Christ's crucifixion,

198
00:12:54,640 --> 00:12:57,420
 establishing a new identity,

199
00:12:57,420 --> 00:13:00,300
 establishing a new identity centered

200
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:04,260
 on Christ's self-giving love manifested on the cross.

201
00:13:04,260 --> 00:13:11,740
 This de-center center becomes the foundation

202
00:13:11,740 --> 00:13:14,980
 for making non-exclusionary judgment

203
00:13:14,980 --> 00:13:17,120
 and combating exclusion.

204
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:22,160
 Wolf concept of embrace,

205
00:13:22,160 --> 00:13:27,560
 based on Romans 15.7,

206
00:13:27,560 --> 00:13:31,400
 welcome one another as Christ has welcomed you.

207
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:36,120
 He sees God's welcoming of humanity

208
00:13:36,120 --> 00:13:40,400
 into divine communion as a model for human relation.

209
00:13:40,400 --> 00:13:45,920
 So God is our model in the way we interact

210
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:47,600
 or we relate to others.

211
00:13:48,940 --> 00:13:53,680
 The ability to choose this will to embrace

212
00:13:53,680 --> 00:13:58,600
 stem from the Holy Spirit work in de-centering the self

213
00:13:58,600 --> 00:14:03,320
 by shaping it in the image of the self-giving Christ

214
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:07,120
 and empowering it to resist the power of exclusion

215
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:10,400
 and the power of the spirit of embrace

216
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:12,340
 and fight it in the self,

217
00:14:12,340 --> 00:14:17,040
 in the structures, and in the culture.

218
00:14:17,780 --> 00:14:20,040
 (coughing)

219
00:14:20,040 --> 00:14:25,780
 Reconciliation succeeds when the self is ready

220
00:14:25,780 --> 00:14:29,380
 to receive the other and adjust its identity

221
00:14:29,380 --> 00:14:32,260
 in light of others' differences.

222
00:14:32,260 --> 00:14:35,900
 We cannot live rightly without welcoming others

223
00:14:35,900 --> 00:14:38,340
 as they are part of our identity,

224
00:14:38,340 --> 00:14:41,640
 reflecting the true God's personality.

225
00:14:41,640 --> 00:14:45,620
 Wolf described the process of welcoming

226
00:14:45,620 --> 00:14:50,160
 with a metaphor of embrace, which symbolized four stages.

227
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:52,800
 Opening arms,

228
00:14:52,800 --> 00:15:00,060
 which means creating space for the other,

229
00:15:00,060 --> 00:15:03,300
 creating space for the other.

230
00:15:03,300 --> 00:15:08,280
 Waiting, the second stage,

231
00:15:08,280 --> 00:15:10,140
 waiting for the other to come.

232
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:13,700
 Indicate differentiation,

233
00:15:13,700 --> 00:15:17,160
 the concept that we just identified.

234
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:21,580
 Closing arms means achieving unity

235
00:15:21,580 --> 00:15:24,700
 through mutual giving and receiving,

236
00:15:24,700 --> 00:15:26,620
 the dialogue, differentiation,

237
00:15:26,620 --> 00:15:28,380
 when we interact with one another.

238
00:15:28,380 --> 00:15:32,900
 Opening arms again, which is very important,

239
00:15:32,900 --> 00:15:38,860
 which means affirming each person's distinct identity.

240
00:15:38,860 --> 00:15:41,780
 So in order to accept the other,

241
00:15:41,780 --> 00:15:43,820
 this does not mean to assimilate,

242
00:15:43,820 --> 00:15:46,500
 this does not mean to lose our identity.

243
00:15:46,500 --> 00:15:51,500
 It actually means that I keep my distinct identity,

244
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:53,820
 but I will have space for the other

245
00:15:53,820 --> 00:15:58,420
 to enter to my identity and give and receive, interact.

246
00:15:58,420 --> 00:16:05,420
 For many settings, now this seems very autopic,

247
00:16:05,420 --> 00:16:07,580
 for many settings, a handshake,

248
00:16:08,900 --> 00:16:13,900
 connecting with people while they are at a safe distance

249
00:16:13,900 --> 00:16:15,820
 is also a form of embrace.

250
00:16:15,820 --> 00:16:19,980
 You know, we need to remember that we live in a fallen world.

251
00:16:19,980 --> 00:16:26,080
 We have our Christian values,

252
00:16:26,080 --> 00:16:29,100
 but even us, because we live in a fallen world

253
00:16:29,100 --> 00:16:33,460
 and we are not complete, incomplete,

254
00:16:33,460 --> 00:16:37,220
 so everything we do, our embrace, our forgiveness,

255
00:16:37,220 --> 00:16:41,320
 our love, our repentance, they are all incomplete.

256
00:16:41,320 --> 00:16:48,380
 So also embrace is also incomplete,

257
00:16:48,380 --> 00:16:51,740
 and sometimes handshake, you know,

258
00:16:51,740 --> 00:16:53,740
 connect with others from a distance,

259
00:16:53,740 --> 00:16:57,660
 it also can be taken as embrace.

260
00:16:57,660 --> 00:17:01,100
 For Wolf, the will to embrace,

261
00:17:01,100 --> 00:17:03,060
 which is forgiveness for him,

262
00:17:03,060 --> 00:17:07,120
 it's unilateral and conditional and free.

263
00:17:07,120 --> 00:17:11,060
 While embrace, which is reconciliation,

264
00:17:11,060 --> 00:17:13,460
 is mutual and conditional,

265
00:17:13,460 --> 00:17:17,900
 require repentance, confession, and reparation.

266
00:17:17,900 --> 00:17:23,460
 There can be no justice without the will to embrace

267
00:17:23,460 --> 00:17:26,240
 and no genuine embrace without justice.

268
00:17:26,240 --> 00:17:32,780
 Now to take Wolf's embrace theology

269
00:17:32,780 --> 00:17:35,900
 from the theoretical level to the practical level,

270
00:17:35,900 --> 00:17:39,740
 I will now introduce Ubuntu, Sulha, and Iguanchi

271
00:17:39,740 --> 00:17:42,620
 that can inform Wolf's embrace theology.

272
00:17:42,620 --> 00:17:48,900
 Okay.

273
00:17:48,900 --> 00:17:52,100
 Ubuntu.

274
00:17:52,100 --> 00:17:55,200
 Ubuntu is an African term.

275
00:17:55,200 --> 00:17:56,980
 It means humanity.

276
00:17:56,980 --> 00:18:01,840
 Often translated as I am who I am

277
00:18:01,840 --> 00:18:03,340
 because of who we are.

278
00:18:03,340 --> 00:18:09,580
 It suggests that human being are deeply interconnected

279
00:18:09,580 --> 00:18:13,040
 and are fully human only in communion with others.

280
00:18:13,040 --> 00:18:17,500
 In other words, a self-identity formed

281
00:18:17,500 --> 00:18:18,940
 through the community.

282
00:18:18,940 --> 00:18:24,220
 This communal identity enables people to discover,

283
00:18:24,220 --> 00:18:27,340
 express, and maintain their full humanity.

284
00:18:28,280 --> 00:18:31,880
 A person's behavior is shaped by its impact

285
00:18:31,880 --> 00:18:35,760
 on the well-being of the community and right relationships,

286
00:18:35,760 --> 00:18:40,600
 often prioritizing communal need over individual ones.

287
00:18:40,600 --> 00:18:42,600
 And this is sometimes, many times,

288
00:18:42,600 --> 00:18:46,740
 this is the maybe the weaknesses in our communal context

289
00:18:46,740 --> 00:18:49,760
 is sometimes for the sake of the communal well-being,

290
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:52,960
 sometimes we sacrifice individuals justice.

291
00:18:55,140 --> 00:18:58,920
 In Ubuntu, justice and forgiveness intertwine

292
00:18:58,920 --> 00:19:00,380
 to restore humanity.

293
00:19:00,380 --> 00:19:04,080
 Humiliation or abuse, for example,

294
00:19:04,080 --> 00:19:07,880
 within a community diminish one's Ubuntu,

295
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:09,980
 diminish one's humanity.

296
00:19:09,980 --> 00:19:13,560
 If there's injustice taking place in a specific community,

297
00:19:13,560 --> 00:19:18,560
 our humanity decreased because other people are suffering.

298
00:19:18,560 --> 00:19:22,720
 And this is why, because we all belong in the greater whole.

299
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:27,960
 This is the way Ubuntu understand humanity.

300
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:31,940
 While seeking revenge would harm one's own Ubuntu,

301
00:19:31,940 --> 00:19:35,380
 forgiveness allows victim to experience the restoration

302
00:19:35,380 --> 00:19:37,540
 of their Ubuntu, freeing them

303
00:19:37,540 --> 00:19:40,460
 from desperation and isolation.

304
00:19:40,460 --> 00:19:44,060
 It's very interesting.

305
00:19:44,060 --> 00:19:46,680
 Forgiveness restores one's Ubuntu,

306
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:49,520
 restores their humanity.

307
00:19:49,520 --> 00:19:53,220
 Through forgiveness, which acknowledge the humanity

308
00:19:53,220 --> 00:19:55,920
 of both victims and perpetrators,

309
00:19:55,920 --> 00:20:00,380
 victims heal and perpetrators acknowledge their wrongdoing,

310
00:20:00,380 --> 00:20:02,780
 reinforcing the interconnectedness

311
00:20:02,780 --> 00:20:06,000
 of human existence with Ubuntu.

312
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:11,860
 In Ubuntu, justice is restorative.

313
00:20:11,860 --> 00:20:16,260
 When someone violates the Ubuntu system,

314
00:20:16,260 --> 00:20:17,920
 the community can redeem them

315
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:21,260
 through forgiveness and repentance.

316
00:20:21,260 --> 00:20:23,500
 Those who don't repent, for example,

317
00:20:23,500 --> 00:20:27,160
 may face temporary exclusion by the community.

318
00:20:27,160 --> 00:20:30,320
 And through forgiveness and reconciliation,

319
00:20:30,320 --> 00:20:33,840
 the community reintegrate both the victim and perpetrators.

320
00:20:33,840 --> 00:20:37,820
 In this way, they reduce the risk of future violence.

321
00:20:37,820 --> 00:20:42,720
 An individual's capacity to forgive

322
00:20:42,720 --> 00:20:44,980
 is not only a personal virtue,

323
00:20:44,980 --> 00:20:47,060
 but also serves the community

324
00:20:47,060 --> 00:20:49,480
 as it enables peace and social harmony.

325
00:20:50,480 --> 00:20:55,480
 Ubuntu sees forgiveness as the only way to achieve justice

326
00:20:55,480 --> 00:20:58,800
 without losing balance in society.

327
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:02,560
 Since only forgiveness can realize Ubuntu,

328
00:21:02,560 --> 00:21:04,880
 it looks forward toward justice

329
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:07,820
 rather than backward toward revenge.

330
00:21:07,820 --> 00:21:13,920
 Therefore, embracing the perpetrator into society

331
00:21:13,920 --> 00:21:16,240
 through forgiveness and reconciliation

332
00:21:16,240 --> 00:21:20,800
 is seen as critical to restoring relationships,

333
00:21:20,800 --> 00:21:24,040
 healing, and to future safety of the community.

334
00:21:24,040 --> 00:21:41,320
 This philosophy found tangible expression

335
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:43,780
 in the Truth and Reconciliation Commission,

336
00:21:45,200 --> 00:21:47,080
 which was established to investigate

337
00:21:47,080 --> 00:21:51,520
 human rights violations committed during apartheid

338
00:21:51,520 --> 00:21:53,160
 and to facilitate reconciliation

339
00:21:53,160 --> 00:21:55,360
 between perpetrators and victims.

340
00:21:55,360 --> 00:21:59,960
 Under this Ubuntu guidance,

341
00:21:59,960 --> 00:22:02,040
 the Truth and Reconciliation Commission

342
00:22:02,040 --> 00:22:06,080
 adopted a restorative justice approach,

343
00:22:06,080 --> 00:22:10,640
 harmonizing Christian teaching on truth,

344
00:22:10,640 --> 00:22:12,800
 justice, and forgiveness

345
00:22:13,860 --> 00:22:16,480
 with the African Ubuntu ethos.

346
00:22:16,480 --> 00:22:19,560
 So this is beautiful to see that

347
00:22:19,560 --> 00:22:22,000
 because Archbishop Tutu,

348
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:25,800
 he also headed the Truth and Reconciliation Commission.

349
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:28,000
 And because he headed that,

350
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:32,500
 he made sure to align with the Christian teaching

351
00:22:32,500 --> 00:22:36,500
 in Truth and Reconciliation Commission.

352
00:22:37,420 --> 00:22:39,580
 (silence)

353
00:22:39,580 --> 00:22:49,540
 The Truth and Reconciliation Commission

354
00:22:49,540 --> 00:22:52,860
 emphasize acknowledging past atrocities,

355
00:22:52,860 --> 00:22:55,920
 confronting injustice, and embracing forgiveness

356
00:22:55,920 --> 00:22:57,980
 to break the cycle of violence

357
00:22:57,980 --> 00:23:02,820
 and rebuild the social fabric torn by apartheid oppression.

358
00:23:02,820 --> 00:23:07,580
 Tutu application of his Christian convictions

359
00:23:07,580 --> 00:23:09,660
 with African cultural values

360
00:23:09,660 --> 00:23:12,140
 led to the development of Ubuntu theology.

361
00:23:12,140 --> 00:23:26,500
 This unique theological framework

362
00:23:26,500 --> 00:23:28,260
 centered on Ubuntu principle

363
00:23:28,260 --> 00:23:30,940
 played a role in challenging apartheid

364
00:23:30,940 --> 00:23:32,980
 through forgiveness and justice.

365
00:23:32,980 --> 00:23:37,020
 Tutu theology emphasized the inherent dignity

366
00:23:37,020 --> 00:23:41,100
 of every individual as created in the image of God,

367
00:23:41,100 --> 00:23:45,260
 reflecting the Christian concept of (speaking in foreign language)

368
00:23:45,260 --> 00:23:46,780
 which means treating others

369
00:23:46,780 --> 00:23:49,760
 with love, compassion, and justice.

370
00:23:49,760 --> 00:23:52,980
 It also recognized the interconnectedness of humanity

371
00:23:52,980 --> 00:23:54,460
 within communities,

372
00:23:54,460 --> 00:23:58,860
 resonating with the Christian principle of communion,

373
00:23:58,860 --> 00:24:00,740
 highlighting the idea of believers

374
00:24:00,740 --> 00:24:04,020
 being part of the one body of Christ.

375
00:24:04,020 --> 00:24:06,780
 In addition, it aligned with Shalom

376
00:24:06,780 --> 00:24:09,900
 of restoring balance and harmony within communities,

377
00:24:09,900 --> 00:24:13,740
 addressing injustice, promoting reconciliation, and healing.

378
00:24:13,740 --> 00:24:19,220
 Sulha.

379
00:24:19,220 --> 00:24:24,220
 Sulha is the Middle Eastern conflict resolution practice.

380
00:24:25,460 --> 00:24:30,460
 It's an Arab word means peace or resolution.

381
00:24:30,460 --> 00:24:34,140
 It's a Middle Eastern tradition approach to reconciliation

382
00:24:34,140 --> 00:24:38,620
 and it refers to a ritualized mediation arbitration process

383
00:24:38,620 --> 00:24:41,580
 for managing a wide range of conflict.

384
00:24:41,580 --> 00:24:44,260
 It complements states judicial procedures

385
00:24:44,260 --> 00:24:47,340
 but does not replace individual responsibility

386
00:24:47,340 --> 00:24:49,620
 which means if the murder took place,

387
00:24:49,620 --> 00:24:53,500
 there will be, the Sulha will take place

388
00:24:53,500 --> 00:24:55,360
 within the community

389
00:24:55,360 --> 00:25:00,360
 and there will be a judicial procedures against the criminal

390
00:25:00,360 --> 00:25:04,460
 so it will be both Sulha and court, okay?

391
00:25:04,460 --> 00:25:10,040
 Sulha prioritize the common good over individual justice,

392
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:15,340
 emphasizing harmony among members.

393
00:25:15,340 --> 00:25:18,380
 It takes the form of a ceremonial covenant meal

394
00:25:18,380 --> 00:25:19,580
 of reconciliation.

395
00:25:19,580 --> 00:25:24,100
 Although it's not mentioned specifically

396
00:25:24,100 --> 00:25:27,260
 but this ancient tradition can be seen

397
00:25:27,260 --> 00:25:30,100
 in many covenantal ceremonies in scripture

398
00:25:30,100 --> 00:25:35,340
 such as the reconciliation meal between Jacob and Laban,

399
00:25:35,340 --> 00:25:38,620
 the ceremonial meal the father prepared

400
00:25:38,620 --> 00:25:42,020
 for the prodigal son, the Lord's Supper, and more.

401
00:25:42,020 --> 00:25:47,460
 Sulha is based on the view that hurting an individual

402
00:25:47,460 --> 00:25:49,460
 means hurting the entire community

403
00:25:49,460 --> 00:25:52,100
 and that injuries between

404
00:25:52,600 --> 00:25:57,000
 individuals and groups will grow

405
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:00,160
 if not acknowledged, repaired, or forgiven.

406
00:26:00,160 --> 00:26:06,020
 This approach allow for relationship preparation

407
00:26:06,020 --> 00:26:11,020
 on a micro level with potential of a macro level impact.

408
00:26:11,020 --> 00:26:15,100
 So what, how Sulha work?

409
00:26:15,100 --> 00:26:16,300
 How does Sulha work?

410
00:26:19,960 --> 00:26:23,680
 Sulha process is initiated by the community.

411
00:26:23,680 --> 00:26:30,560
 It's initiated by community representative called Jaha.

412
00:26:30,560 --> 00:26:35,460
 Jaha are notable people in the community.

413
00:26:35,460 --> 00:26:39,680
 When they are authorized by the parties,

414
00:26:39,680 --> 00:26:42,320
 the burden of the conflict shift

415
00:26:42,320 --> 00:26:44,840
 from the parties to the Jaha.

416
00:26:46,080 --> 00:26:51,080
 In other words, when the community become responsible

417
00:26:51,080 --> 00:26:57,620
 for dealing with, for managing this conflict,

418
00:26:57,620 --> 00:27:00,080
 all the burden of the conflict will be shifted

419
00:27:00,080 --> 00:27:02,240
 from the party to the community

420
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:04,680
 and the community become responsible

421
00:27:04,680 --> 00:27:06,080
 to deal with this conflict.

422
00:27:06,080 --> 00:27:09,920
 Now what is the goal of the Jaha?

423
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:15,720
 The goal of the Jaha is to transform forgiveness

424
00:27:15,720 --> 00:27:18,080
 from a private affair to a public one.

425
00:27:18,080 --> 00:27:22,200
 If eventually through the process,

426
00:27:22,200 --> 00:27:24,840
 dignity is increased and forgiveness

427
00:27:24,840 --> 00:27:26,760
 gradually replace revenge,

428
00:27:26,760 --> 00:27:29,420
 a peace agreement will be made

429
00:27:29,420 --> 00:27:31,620
 in a public reconciliation ceremony.

430
00:27:31,620 --> 00:27:35,680
 Sulha function as a social mechanism

431
00:27:35,680 --> 00:27:37,740
 for the promotion of forgiveness.

432
00:27:37,740 --> 00:27:39,440
 When a conflict break out,

433
00:27:39,440 --> 00:27:42,480
 the Jaha recruits the victim family

434
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:44,320
 into the Sulha process,

435
00:27:44,320 --> 00:27:46,200
 achieve a ceasefire,

436
00:27:46,200 --> 00:27:47,840
 start investigation,

437
00:27:47,840 --> 00:27:50,240
 and gradually convince the disputant

438
00:27:50,240 --> 00:27:52,080
 that their honor will be restored

439
00:27:52,080 --> 00:27:57,080
 if they forgive more than if they seek vengeance.

440
00:27:57,080 --> 00:28:01,040
 So it's dialogue,

441
00:28:01,040 --> 00:28:03,120
 try to convince them,

442
00:28:03,120 --> 00:28:05,960
 see if you forgive,

443
00:28:05,960 --> 00:28:07,960
 it's better than if you revenge.

444
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:11,560
 And after the Jaha,

445
00:28:12,680 --> 00:28:15,360
 finally in a public reconciliation ceremony,

446
00:28:15,360 --> 00:28:22,080
 the Jaha become communal guardians.

447
00:28:22,080 --> 00:28:24,640
 They are not only taking the burden

448
00:28:24,640 --> 00:28:26,900
 of the conflict on them,

449
00:28:26,900 --> 00:28:31,160
 but they become communal guardians

450
00:28:31,160 --> 00:28:32,480
 of the reconciliation.

451
00:28:32,480 --> 00:28:35,600
 They protect the peace

452
00:28:35,600 --> 00:28:39,440
 after they try to achieve it.

453
00:28:40,400 --> 00:28:43,740
 Emphasizing compromise, forgiveness, and peace.

454
00:28:43,740 --> 00:28:52,780
 The Sulha process includes community engagement

455
00:28:52,780 --> 00:28:53,840
 and rituals.

456
00:28:53,840 --> 00:28:59,360
 It includes venting rituals

457
00:28:59,360 --> 00:29:00,960
 which allow the victim's family

458
00:29:00,960 --> 00:29:03,760
 to express emotions.

459
00:29:03,760 --> 00:29:07,120
 So venting is something very important

460
00:29:07,120 --> 00:29:08,360
 when there is conflict.

461
00:29:08,360 --> 00:29:11,400
 You need to give space to venting.

462
00:29:11,400 --> 00:29:13,320
 And it's also biblical,

463
00:29:13,320 --> 00:29:15,120
 it's lamentation, right?

464
00:29:15,120 --> 00:29:19,800
 So the Jaha start the process

465
00:29:19,800 --> 00:29:23,160
 after they convince for ceasefire

466
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:26,160
 and they try to convince them

467
00:29:26,160 --> 00:29:30,340
 to move from revenge to forgiveness,

468
00:29:30,340 --> 00:29:31,980
 they start the process.

469
00:29:31,980 --> 00:29:37,320
 So venting rituals allow

470
00:29:37,320 --> 00:29:41,240
 the victim's family to express emotions,

471
00:29:41,240 --> 00:29:44,560
 shifting from vengeance to forgiveness.

472
00:29:44,560 --> 00:29:45,880
 Through reverse Musayrah,

473
00:29:45,880 --> 00:29:48,000
 the Jaha plead for forgiveness

474
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:49,740
 on behalf of the offender.

475
00:29:49,740 --> 00:29:54,000
 And listen to this,

476
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:57,120
 they are acting as anger absorber

477
00:29:57,120 --> 00:29:58,400
 of their pain.

478
00:29:58,400 --> 00:30:03,440
 So the Jaha, which is community representative,

479
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:06,260
 they don't only take the conflict on them,

480
00:30:07,220 --> 00:30:10,660
 they also act as an anger absorber

481
00:30:10,660 --> 00:30:11,780
 of their pain,

482
00:30:11,780 --> 00:30:13,260
 which restores honor

483
00:30:13,260 --> 00:30:15,860
 and ease feeling of humiliation.

484
00:30:15,860 --> 00:30:20,220
 It's like the notable people of the community

485
00:30:20,220 --> 00:30:22,660
 will come to this family

486
00:30:22,660 --> 00:30:25,460
 and beg them to forgive,

487
00:30:25,460 --> 00:30:28,180
 and they take the responsibility

488
00:30:28,180 --> 00:30:32,300
 in terms of leading it to a ceasefire

489
00:30:32,300 --> 00:30:35,220
 and reconciliation process,

490
00:30:35,220 --> 00:30:37,940
 but they also act as an anger absorber.

491
00:30:37,940 --> 00:30:40,040
 They can sit for days

492
00:30:40,040 --> 00:30:42,820
 and listen to them as they vent.

493
00:30:42,820 --> 00:30:46,480
 The Jaha also employ honor rituals

494
00:30:46,480 --> 00:30:48,380
 through the whole process.

495
00:30:48,380 --> 00:30:51,060
 These rituals acknowledge suffering

496
00:30:51,060 --> 00:30:53,920
 as a consequence of forgiveness.

497
00:30:53,920 --> 00:30:56,980
 And this also remind us,

498
00:30:56,980 --> 00:30:59,320
 forgiveness is a form of suffering.

499
00:30:59,320 --> 00:31:02,020
 When we forgive, we suffer.

500
00:31:03,020 --> 00:31:05,820
 (silence)

501
00:31:05,820 --> 00:31:08,480
 Sulha ceremonies include public rituals.

502
00:31:08,480 --> 00:31:12,260
 Ceremonies are held outdoors

503
00:31:12,260 --> 00:31:13,580
 in the village center,

504
00:31:13,580 --> 00:31:15,860
 where disputants,

505
00:31:15,860 --> 00:31:20,580
 venting, honor rituals,

506
00:31:20,580 --> 00:31:22,620
 ceremony in the village center.

507
00:31:22,620 --> 00:31:24,900
 Sulha ceremony includes public rituals.

508
00:31:24,900 --> 00:31:26,620
 Now we are at the ceremony.

509
00:31:26,620 --> 00:31:29,820
 Ceremonies are held outdoor

510
00:31:29,820 --> 00:31:31,380
 in the village center.

511
00:31:32,220 --> 00:31:33,860
 Where disputants' family

512
00:31:33,860 --> 00:31:35,660
 and community leaders,

513
00:31:35,660 --> 00:31:37,420
 sometimes include the police

514
00:31:37,420 --> 00:31:42,220
 and includes leaders from other religion,

515
00:31:42,220 --> 00:31:43,660
 includes the families of course,

516
00:31:43,660 --> 00:31:45,700
 and the Jaha,

517
00:31:45,700 --> 00:31:48,060
 as they sign peace agreement

518
00:31:48,060 --> 00:31:50,380
 ensuring public visibility

519
00:31:50,380 --> 00:31:52,220
 and honor restoration.

520
00:31:52,220 --> 00:31:55,520
 So public visibility here is very important.

521
00:31:55,520 --> 00:32:01,080
 Ceremonies include three ceremonic acts.

522
00:32:02,080 --> 00:32:06,520
 Musafaha, which means a handshake

523
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:08,440
 between the disputant.

524
00:32:08,440 --> 00:32:13,540
 Musamaha, which means forgiveness declaration.

525
00:32:13,540 --> 00:32:19,260
 And Mumalaha, which means a ceremonial meal.

526
00:32:19,260 --> 00:32:27,420
 During a heavy silent ritual,

527
00:32:27,420 --> 00:32:30,460
 both parties express humility.

528
00:32:30,460 --> 00:32:33,460
 The offender's family admit wrongdoing

529
00:32:33,460 --> 00:32:35,500
 and offer compensation,

530
00:32:35,500 --> 00:32:38,340
 while the victim's family declare forgiveness.

531
00:32:38,340 --> 00:32:41,680
 Community involvement and guidance

532
00:32:41,680 --> 00:32:43,240
 through the public ritual

533
00:32:43,240 --> 00:32:46,000
 are integral to the Sulha process.

534
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:49,120
 Where forgiveness is expressed

535
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:50,880
 through collective activities

536
00:32:50,880 --> 00:32:53,120
 and religious practices.

537
00:32:53,120 --> 00:32:56,080
 Sulha provide a culturally appropriate means

538
00:32:56,080 --> 00:32:59,680
 for restoring value.

539
00:33:00,620 --> 00:33:03,660
 Sulha gradually ritualize

540
00:33:03,660 --> 00:33:05,540
 the following experience.

541
00:33:05,540 --> 00:33:09,460
 Again, Sulha gradually ritualize

542
00:33:09,460 --> 00:33:11,860
 the following experiences.

543
00:33:11,860 --> 00:33:16,420
 It acknowledge pain during the venting rituals.

544
00:33:16,420 --> 00:33:18,500
 It condemn wrong.

545
00:33:18,500 --> 00:33:19,940
 It achieve justice,

546
00:33:19,940 --> 00:33:21,940
 because there is,

547
00:33:21,940 --> 00:33:23,420
 we said there is the investigation

548
00:33:23,420 --> 00:33:25,220
 and there is the verdict after that.

549
00:33:25,220 --> 00:33:29,200
 It ritualize offering forgiveness,

550
00:33:29,200 --> 00:33:31,700
 as we saw at the three symbolic acts.

551
00:33:31,700 --> 00:33:36,160
 And these rituals

552
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:38,500
 and these experiences

553
00:33:38,500 --> 00:33:43,420
 are seen and heard publicly

554
00:33:43,420 --> 00:33:47,740
 with the whole community present

555
00:33:47,740 --> 00:33:49,540
 and it become binding.

556
00:33:49,540 --> 00:33:53,300
 Which means,

557
00:33:53,300 --> 00:33:55,140
 even

558
00:33:58,220 --> 00:34:02,140
 if the victim's family still have resentment,

559
00:34:02,140 --> 00:34:03,480
 probably,

560
00:34:03,480 --> 00:34:04,320
 hatred,

561
00:34:04,320 --> 00:34:07,980
 feeling of revenge,

562
00:34:07,980 --> 00:34:11,380
 if they enter this process,

563
00:34:11,380 --> 00:34:14,780
 it become binding.

564
00:34:14,780 --> 00:34:24,020
 So,

565
00:34:24,020 --> 00:34:27,080
 if a family member from the victim's family

566
00:34:27,080 --> 00:34:31,020
 revenge and he work against the agreement,

567
00:34:31,020 --> 00:34:34,800
 it will be a huge humiliation for the family.

568
00:34:34,800 --> 00:34:36,400
 So, they will not do it.

569
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:37,960
 Probably, they will not do it.

570
00:34:37,960 --> 00:34:42,400
 This communal support

571
00:34:42,400 --> 00:34:48,640
 and ritualization may make apology

572
00:34:48,640 --> 00:34:50,840
 and reparation easier to achieve.

573
00:34:50,840 --> 00:34:55,400
 And therefore, facilitate social reconciliation

574
00:34:55,400 --> 00:34:58,160
 or at least diplomatic reconciliation,

575
00:34:58,160 --> 00:34:59,920
 or if you wish social order,

576
00:34:59,920 --> 00:35:05,040
 at least stop the circle of violence,

577
00:35:05,040 --> 00:35:06,820
 which is also good.

578
00:35:06,820 --> 00:35:11,160
 Sulha illustrate that forgiveness

579
00:35:11,160 --> 00:35:13,460
 can be catalyzed externally

580
00:35:13,460 --> 00:35:16,680
 by community initiated process,

581
00:35:16,680 --> 00:35:19,200
 paving the way for internal forgiveness.

582
00:35:19,200 --> 00:35:21,880
 Rather than rigidly defining forgiveness,

583
00:35:21,880 --> 00:35:24,420
 it explore diverse avenues,

584
00:35:24,420 --> 00:35:28,860
 such as action, rituals, words, and public confession.

585
00:35:28,860 --> 00:35:34,120
 Encouraging transformative change in attitude,

586
00:35:34,120 --> 00:35:37,200
 in emotion, leading to empathy.

587
00:35:37,200 --> 00:35:38,600
 So, it's kind of like

588
00:35:38,600 --> 00:35:43,260
 forcing people to think about forgiveness,

589
00:35:43,260 --> 00:35:45,200
 even if they don't want.

590
00:35:45,200 --> 00:35:47,280
 But it proves it works.

591
00:35:47,280 --> 00:35:50,560
 So, in other words,

592
00:35:50,560 --> 00:35:53,280
 forgiveness can start externally

593
00:35:53,280 --> 00:35:58,080
 and slowly it can grow into the internal forgiveness.

594
00:35:58,080 --> 00:36:08,920
 I identify four elements of, if you wish,

595
00:36:08,920 --> 00:36:11,200
 I call it Sulha theology.

596
00:36:11,200 --> 00:36:13,360
 So, I start to develop this concept

597
00:36:13,360 --> 00:36:17,200
 in an article I wrote for the DeGroter Encyclopedia

598
00:36:17,200 --> 00:36:21,920
 on Middle Eastern Christian and Peacemaking.

599
00:36:21,920 --> 00:36:26,000
 So, I found four elements that are important

600
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:28,520
 to be included in Sulha theology.

601
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:30,460
 First, community.

602
00:36:30,460 --> 00:36:33,600
 Community can bear the burden of the wrong done

603
00:36:33,600 --> 00:36:37,320
 together.

604
00:36:37,320 --> 00:36:40,880
 The community act as an anger absorber in this way,

605
00:36:40,880 --> 00:36:42,960
 restoring and embracing other

606
00:36:42,960 --> 00:36:45,360
 and repentant,

607
00:36:45,360 --> 00:36:49,120
 restoring and embracing both the victims

608
00:36:49,120 --> 00:36:51,680
 and repentant perpetrators.

609
00:36:51,680 --> 00:36:54,300
 Therefore, reconciliation takes place,

610
00:36:54,300 --> 00:36:55,700
 and listen to this,

611
00:36:55,700 --> 00:37:00,200
 not in that triangle of God, offender, offended,

612
00:37:00,200 --> 00:37:01,960
 but

613
00:37:01,960 --> 00:37:07,600
 in Rambos, that includes also God, also the community.

614
00:37:07,600 --> 00:37:13,080
 So, basically, in many Western reconciliation theologies,

615
00:37:13,080 --> 00:37:14,880
 reconciliation takes place

616
00:37:14,880 --> 00:37:17,360
 in the triangle of God, offender, offended.

617
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:20,880
 And in this way, including the community

618
00:37:20,880 --> 00:37:24,800
 as an important part of facilitating

619
00:37:24,800 --> 00:37:26,280
 and leading to reconciliation,

620
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:29,840
 and then in this context, reconciliation takes place

621
00:37:29,840 --> 00:37:33,760
 in Rambos, which is God,

622
00:37:33,760 --> 00:37:36,560
 offender's family, offended family,

623
00:37:36,560 --> 00:37:39,340
 and the community that hold the process.

624
00:37:39,340 --> 00:37:44,320
 Venting or lamentation names and

625
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:48,360
 condemns the wrong.

626
00:37:49,980 --> 00:37:52,680
 It provides a space for anger and pain

627
00:37:52,680 --> 00:37:55,100
 to be expressed and transformed,

628
00:37:55,100 --> 00:37:58,600
 thereby enabling the reversal of dignity violation

629
00:37:58,600 --> 00:38:00,360
 through a public acknowledgement

630
00:38:00,360 --> 00:38:02,760
 of the moral standing of the offended.

631
00:38:02,760 --> 00:38:08,040
 So, venting is important because we need to name the wrong,

632
00:38:08,040 --> 00:38:11,220
 and if we are suffering,

633
00:38:11,220 --> 00:38:14,760
 it's very important to express our emotion,

634
00:38:14,760 --> 00:38:16,460
 and this is what is lamentation.

635
00:38:19,220 --> 00:38:21,060
 Dignity restoration.

636
00:38:21,060 --> 00:38:26,040
 Release pain and heals shame.

637
00:38:26,040 --> 00:38:28,560
 When you restore the dignity of somebody,

638
00:38:28,560 --> 00:38:32,280
 it release pain and it heals shame.

639
00:38:32,280 --> 00:38:34,880
 Publicly affirming the dignity of the other

640
00:38:34,880 --> 00:38:37,600
 in the community context is vital

641
00:38:37,600 --> 00:38:39,580
 in restoring broken relationship

642
00:38:39,580 --> 00:38:41,120
 and essential for healing.

643
00:38:41,120 --> 00:38:44,940
 And lastly, rituals.

644
00:38:46,100 --> 00:38:50,420
 Rituals reinforce collective values and transform us.

645
00:38:50,420 --> 00:38:53,680
 I will be talking about it later.

646
00:38:53,680 --> 00:38:57,560
 Through church liturgy, rituals,

647
00:38:57,560 --> 00:39:02,040
 the word of God work in the minds and heart

648
00:39:02,040 --> 00:39:05,360
 and transform our memories, desires, and attitude

649
00:39:05,360 --> 00:39:09,280
 toward truth, repentance, forgiveness, and reconciliation.

650
00:39:09,280 --> 00:39:12,900
 We'll be talking about all this more,

651
00:39:12,900 --> 00:39:15,320
 so I want to move now to Gwanchi.

652
00:39:16,320 --> 00:39:18,820
 So, (laughs)

653
00:39:18,820 --> 00:39:26,560
 so I'm not an expert on this topic.

654
00:39:26,560 --> 00:39:29,840
 I've just come to learn about it

655
00:39:29,840 --> 00:39:34,140
 when I wrote my article or my paper.

656
00:39:34,140 --> 00:39:38,260
 I have read a little bit about it,

657
00:39:38,260 --> 00:39:43,340
 but I thought it would be maybe more engaging

658
00:39:43,340 --> 00:39:47,600
 to incorporate it as another cultural perspective

659
00:39:47,600 --> 00:39:51,560
 that we can learn from, and you can also interact

660
00:39:51,560 --> 00:39:54,380
 with other cultural perspective,

661
00:39:54,380 --> 00:39:58,660
 but some familiar perspective for you.

662
00:39:58,660 --> 00:39:59,600
 So, let's see.

663
00:39:59,600 --> 00:40:01,920
 I want to learn from you more about it,

664
00:40:01,920 --> 00:40:06,400
 but let me give you some introduction about it.

665
00:40:06,400 --> 00:40:07,240
 Gwanchi,

666
00:40:10,600 --> 00:40:13,540
 Gwanchi, a framework of relationship and peace building.

667
00:40:13,540 --> 00:40:15,360
 This is the way I called it.

668
00:40:15,360 --> 00:40:18,060
 Gwanchi means relationship or connection,

669
00:40:18,060 --> 00:40:22,500
 is a deeply rooted Chinese system of social relationship

670
00:40:22,500 --> 00:40:26,580
 shaped by confusion ideology of kinship paradigm

671
00:40:26,580 --> 00:40:29,260
 regarding the rights and responsibilities

672
00:40:29,260 --> 00:40:30,620
 of people to each other.

673
00:40:30,620 --> 00:40:36,500
 It emphasized trust, social obligation, and reciprocity

674
00:40:36,500 --> 00:40:38,700
 as the foundation of social harmony.

675
00:40:38,700 --> 00:40:43,700
 Gwanchi is guided by six core confusion values,

676
00:40:43,700 --> 00:40:54,540
 moral cultivation, interpersonal relationship,

677
00:40:54,540 --> 00:40:58,300
 family orientation, respect for age and hierarchy,

678
00:40:58,300 --> 00:41:01,660
 avoiding conflict, and maintaining peace.

679
00:41:01,660 --> 00:41:04,360
 Some of them are very similar in my culture, actually.

680
00:41:04,360 --> 00:41:08,220
 Gwanchi highlights interconnectedness.

681
00:41:08,220 --> 00:41:13,220
 It views individuals as part of a web of social interaction

682
00:41:13,220 --> 00:41:18,460
 and prioritize collective interest

683
00:41:18,460 --> 00:41:20,540
 and harmony over individualism.

684
00:41:20,540 --> 00:41:25,420
 Gwanchi, which is traditionally centered on family,

685
00:41:25,420 --> 00:41:28,220
 has expanded into business and politics.

686
00:41:28,220 --> 00:41:30,460
 Relationships are built and sustained

687
00:41:30,460 --> 00:41:36,240
 through ongoing exchange of favor, gifts, and interaction

688
00:41:36,240 --> 00:41:40,100
 driven by loyalty and trust rather than pure utility.

689
00:41:40,100 --> 00:41:47,580
 Everyday rituals like banquets, gift giving,

690
00:41:47,580 --> 00:41:49,820
 visiting during special occasions,

691
00:41:49,820 --> 00:41:53,500
 and showing respect to elders foster emotional bonds,

692
00:41:53,500 --> 00:41:58,560
 mediate tension, and strengthen social cohesion.

693
00:41:58,560 --> 00:42:04,100
 These practices, both symbolic and practical,

694
00:42:05,620 --> 00:42:09,000
 create an environment of interdependence

695
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:10,800
 and relationship balance.

696
00:42:10,800 --> 00:42:16,380
 Unlike Ubuntu, which emphasized universal humanity,

697
00:42:16,380 --> 00:42:21,380
 and Sulha, which uses formal rituals for reconciliation,

698
00:42:21,380 --> 00:42:25,660
 Gwanchi flourished in informal, localized sitting.

699
00:42:25,660 --> 00:42:31,100
 In confusion thoughts, rituals and virtues,

700
00:42:31,100 --> 00:42:35,380
 like benevolence, are vital for a just society,

701
00:42:35,380 --> 00:42:38,840
 shaping moral character and promoting harmony.

702
00:42:38,840 --> 00:42:43,040
 Rituals include social norms and behaviors.

703
00:42:43,040 --> 00:42:45,360
 Through rituals, people embed respect,

704
00:42:45,360 --> 00:42:51,360
 consideration, and creating a harmonious environment.

705
00:42:51,360 --> 00:42:54,120
 Through virtue, on the other hand,

706
00:42:54,120 --> 00:42:57,580
 it guides moral qualities individuals should cultivate.

707
00:42:57,580 --> 00:43:01,440
 Aligning conduct with these values

708
00:43:01,440 --> 00:43:03,940
 ensure justice in daily life.

709
00:43:03,940 --> 00:43:06,880
 However, Gwanchi can face ethical challenges

710
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:10,440
 like favoritism and corruption

711
00:43:10,440 --> 00:43:13,280
 when personal connection undermine merit.

712
00:43:13,280 --> 00:43:16,560
 Balancing these practices with ethics,

713
00:43:16,560 --> 00:43:20,160
 standard, guarantee fairness, and accountability.

714
00:43:20,160 --> 00:43:24,700
 Gwanchi also offered valuable lessons for peace building.

715
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:34,500
 It emphasized its emphasis on trust, reciprocity,

716
00:43:34,500 --> 00:43:39,220
 and dignity, support, dialogue, and conflict prevention.

717
00:43:39,220 --> 00:43:43,100
 Protecting face, foster trust and harmony,

718
00:43:43,100 --> 00:43:46,100
 while core values such as loyalty, respect,

719
00:43:46,100 --> 00:43:47,940
 benevolence, and righteousness

720
00:43:47,940 --> 00:43:49,960
 promote forgiveness and justice.

721
00:43:59,180 --> 00:44:01,320
 When we compare it with Christian theology,

722
00:44:01,320 --> 00:44:03,880
 the interconnectedness of Gwanchi

723
00:44:03,880 --> 00:44:08,120
 mirror the unity and mutual respect of the true God,

724
00:44:08,120 --> 00:44:10,280
 the ultimate source of all relation.

725
00:44:10,280 --> 00:44:16,360
 Gwanchi also embody early church practices

726
00:44:16,360 --> 00:44:20,000
 of mutual care and shared resources.

727
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:23,320
 And third, Gwanchi echo Christian teaching on shalom,

728
00:44:23,320 --> 00:44:25,360
 where peace is holistic and integrate

729
00:44:25,360 --> 00:44:27,400
 justice and balance relationship.

730
00:44:27,400 --> 00:44:30,160
 (pages rustling)

731
00:44:30,160 --> 00:44:38,980
 Indigenous Chinese Protestant group,

732
00:44:38,980 --> 00:44:41,220
 and I read that in one article actually,

733
00:44:41,220 --> 00:44:44,580
 has adapted Gwanchi to align with Christian teaching,

734
00:44:44,580 --> 00:44:48,460
 reshaping its element to reflect biblical values.

735
00:44:48,460 --> 00:44:53,380
 Family ties are redefined to include all believers

736
00:44:53,380 --> 00:44:56,260
 as part of God's family,

737
00:44:56,260 --> 00:45:00,400
 breaking distinction between close and distant relationship.

738
00:45:00,400 --> 00:45:09,700
 Resource sharing emphasize biblical generosity

739
00:45:09,700 --> 00:45:14,780
 and communal living, moving beyond traditional reciprocity.

740
00:45:14,780 --> 00:45:17,220
 And third, social interaction,

741
00:45:17,220 --> 00:45:22,500
 rituals prioritize spiritual growth

742
00:45:22,500 --> 00:45:25,680
 and Christian ethics over societal norms.

743
00:45:25,680 --> 00:45:28,700
 By bridging Gwanchi cultural values

744
00:45:28,700 --> 00:45:31,820
 with Christian theology, we see how relationship,

745
00:45:31,820 --> 00:45:34,840
 trust, and harmony can become powerful tool

746
00:45:34,840 --> 00:45:37,740
 for encouraging peace, justice, and unity

747
00:45:37,740 --> 00:45:39,620
 within both society and church.

748
00:45:39,620 --> 00:45:50,780
 Okay, reconciliation is as much about

749
00:45:50,780 --> 00:45:55,420
 restoring relationship as it is about transforming identity.

750
00:45:55,880 --> 00:46:00,200
 Whether through VOLF, CALL, to embrace the other,

751
00:46:00,200 --> 00:46:02,520
 Ubuntu's communal solidarity,

752
00:46:02,520 --> 00:46:05,280
 Sulha ritualized dignity restoration,

753
00:46:05,280 --> 00:46:07,760
 or Gwanchi relational harmony,

754
00:46:07,760 --> 00:46:11,520
 each framework offer tools for navigating conflict.

755
00:46:11,520 --> 00:46:14,000
 I will compare these approaches

756
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:16,600
 to highlight their unique contribution

757
00:46:16,600 --> 00:46:20,020
 and potential interaction in the pursuit of peace.

758
00:46:20,020 --> 00:46:23,480
 Common themes.

759
00:46:23,860 --> 00:46:28,860
 First, identity and interconnectedness.

760
00:46:28,860 --> 00:46:34,300
 It's emphasized in the four approaches.

761
00:46:34,300 --> 00:46:41,580
 Embrace, Sulha, Ubuntu, and Gwanchi.

762
00:46:41,580 --> 00:46:44,460
 VOLF argue that true reconciliation begin

763
00:46:44,460 --> 00:46:47,340
 when we embrace other, reshaping our identity

764
00:46:47,340 --> 00:46:50,940
 to make space for their differences,

765
00:46:50,940 --> 00:46:54,380
 mirroring God's inclusive love for all humanity.

766
00:46:54,380 --> 00:46:57,800
 This is not assimilation, but a delicate dance

767
00:46:57,800 --> 00:46:59,940
 of inclusion and distinction.

768
00:46:59,940 --> 00:47:03,580
 Ubuntu reinforced this by declaring,

769
00:47:03,580 --> 00:47:06,620
 I am because we are, meaning human,

770
00:47:06,620 --> 00:47:12,760
 meaning human identity is not an isolated phenomenon,

771
00:47:12,760 --> 00:47:15,940
 but emerged from community.

772
00:47:15,940 --> 00:47:19,140
 Ubuntu goes a step further than VOLF

773
00:47:19,140 --> 00:47:21,060
 by placing communal well-being

774
00:47:21,060 --> 00:47:22,940
 at the center of reconciliation.

775
00:47:22,940 --> 00:47:27,420
 Sulha and Gwanchi offer complementarist insights.

776
00:47:27,420 --> 00:47:32,420
 Sulha sees identity as interwoven with dignity.

777
00:47:32,420 --> 00:47:36,820
 When violated, the entire community is wounded.

778
00:47:36,820 --> 00:47:40,060
 Therefore, reconciliation ritual restored dignity

779
00:47:40,060 --> 00:47:42,180
 and communal harmony.

780
00:47:42,180 --> 00:47:45,500
 Gwanchi highlight relational network

781
00:47:45,500 --> 00:47:48,540
 where dignity is shaped within relationship

782
00:47:48,540 --> 00:47:51,580
 built on trust and reciprocity,

783
00:47:51,580 --> 00:47:54,540
 enabling people to navigate complex social network

784
00:47:54,540 --> 00:47:55,820
 while seeking harmony.

785
00:47:55,820 --> 00:48:01,480
 The second thing is forgiveness and restoration.

786
00:48:01,480 --> 00:48:06,380
 Forgiveness is essential for restoring relationship

787
00:48:06,380 --> 00:48:08,260
 in the four approaches.

788
00:48:08,260 --> 00:48:11,220
 While VOLF highlight the power of forgiveness

789
00:48:11,220 --> 00:48:14,980
 in breaking exclusion cycles and embracing others,

790
00:48:14,980 --> 00:48:17,940
 modeling Christ's sacrifice love,

791
00:48:17,940 --> 00:48:20,820
 Ubuntu sees forgiveness as a communal act,

792
00:48:20,820 --> 00:48:25,080
 restoring both victims and perpetrators humanity.

793
00:48:25,080 --> 00:48:30,700
 Similarly, Sulha frames forgiveness as a communal process

794
00:48:30,700 --> 00:48:32,980
 facilitated by public rituals,

795
00:48:32,980 --> 00:48:35,700
 restoring dignity and social order.

796
00:48:35,700 --> 00:48:40,700
 Ubuntu and Sulha approach align with Gwanchi's goal

797
00:48:40,700 --> 00:48:43,380
 of establishing balance and respect.

798
00:48:43,380 --> 00:48:47,780
 However, Gwanchi principles sustain forgiveness

799
00:48:47,780 --> 00:48:51,820
 through continuous daily practices of exchange

800
00:48:51,820 --> 00:48:56,160
 that mediate tension, reaffirm trust and ethical commitment.

801
00:48:56,160 --> 00:49:01,360
 Third, justice and reconciliation.

802
00:49:01,360 --> 00:49:04,900
 Justice and reconciliation are intertwined

803
00:49:04,900 --> 00:49:07,900
 in all the four approaches,

804
00:49:07,900 --> 00:49:10,100
 each with different emphasis.

805
00:49:13,860 --> 00:49:18,040
 For VOLF, justice is necessary,

806
00:49:18,040 --> 00:49:19,820
 justice initiate forgiveness,

807
00:49:19,820 --> 00:49:23,500
 but true reconciliation cannot happen without justice.

808
00:49:23,500 --> 00:49:26,720
 Ubuntu view justice as restorative,

809
00:49:26,720 --> 00:49:30,100
 it seeks to restore humanity for both victim

810
00:49:30,100 --> 00:49:32,180
 and perpetrator within the community

811
00:49:32,180 --> 00:49:35,980
 by acknowledging atrocities, condemn injustice,

812
00:49:35,980 --> 00:49:38,620
 extend forgiveness, foster healing,

813
00:49:38,620 --> 00:49:41,320
 and rebuild the social fabric.

814
00:49:41,320 --> 00:49:43,860
 Similarly, Sulha achieved justice

815
00:49:43,860 --> 00:49:45,860
 through communal reconciliation,

816
00:49:45,860 --> 00:49:49,620
 where forgiveness restores honor and social order.

817
00:49:49,620 --> 00:49:53,780
 While Ubuntu and Sulha focus on restorative justice,

818
00:49:53,780 --> 00:49:57,420
 Gwanchi offers relationship-based justice,

819
00:49:57,420 --> 00:50:01,300
 rooted in fairness, trust, integrity, and harmony,

820
00:50:01,300 --> 00:50:03,780
 reflecting social justice principle.

821
00:50:03,780 --> 00:50:09,800
 So what is the difference between the four approaches?

822
00:50:10,980 --> 00:50:15,920
 The difference is, first, the cultural context.

823
00:50:15,920 --> 00:50:19,260
 VOLF embraced theology,

824
00:50:19,260 --> 00:50:21,900
 integrates Western individualistic theology

825
00:50:21,900 --> 00:50:24,140
 with contemporary cultural insight.

826
00:50:24,140 --> 00:50:28,980
 Ubuntu, from South African culture,

827
00:50:28,980 --> 00:50:30,800
 emphasize communal values

828
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:33,660
 and interconnectedness in reconciliation.

829
00:50:33,660 --> 00:50:35,860
 Sulha rooted in Middle Eastern tradition

830
00:50:35,860 --> 00:50:40,420
 highlight communal rituals and dignity in reconciliation.

831
00:50:40,420 --> 00:50:44,540
 Gwanchi, based on Confucian Chinese values,

832
00:50:44,540 --> 00:50:46,380
 it highlights traditional network

833
00:50:46,380 --> 00:50:48,700
 based on mutual obligation, trust,

834
00:50:48,700 --> 00:50:50,500
 and faith in reconciliation.

835
00:50:50,500 --> 00:50:58,400
 The second difference between the four approaches

836
00:50:58,400 --> 00:51:00,460
 is the issue of rituals.

837
00:51:00,460 --> 00:51:03,340
 They differ in their focus on rituals, actually.

838
00:51:03,340 --> 00:51:04,780
 While VOLF embraced theology,

839
00:51:04,780 --> 00:51:08,820
 prioritized internal transformation

840
00:51:08,820 --> 00:51:11,140
 and embodying Christ-like love

841
00:51:11,140 --> 00:51:13,660
 in individual and communal life,

842
00:51:13,660 --> 00:51:16,020
 Ubuntu values communal action

843
00:51:16,020 --> 00:51:18,380
 that strengthen social harmony

844
00:51:18,380 --> 00:51:20,840
 and reaffirm humanity within the community.

845
00:51:20,840 --> 00:51:25,140
 Sulha relies on structured public rituals,

846
00:51:25,140 --> 00:51:27,640
 such as venting and ceremonial meal

847
00:51:27,640 --> 00:51:31,340
 to facilitate forgiveness and restore dignity.

848
00:51:31,340 --> 00:51:35,140
 Gwanchi operate through informal daily practices,

849
00:51:35,140 --> 00:51:39,300
 banquets, gift-giving, home visits, and favor exchange

850
00:51:39,300 --> 00:51:43,200
 that nurture trust, interdependence, and social cohesion.

851
00:51:43,200 --> 00:51:48,920
 Community participation is another difference

852
00:51:48,920 --> 00:51:51,640
 between the four approaches.

853
00:51:51,640 --> 00:51:54,980
 The level and nature of community involvement

854
00:51:54,980 --> 00:51:58,020
 differ across the four approaches.

855
00:51:58,020 --> 00:52:01,700
 VOLF highlights the responsibility of individuals

856
00:52:01,700 --> 00:52:04,420
 and churches to embody Christ's love

857
00:52:04,420 --> 00:52:07,660
 and advance reconciliation in diverse contexts.

858
00:52:07,660 --> 00:52:10,380
 In Ubuntu and Sulha, however,

859
00:52:10,380 --> 00:52:13,780
 community involvement is integral to the process.

860
00:52:13,780 --> 00:52:17,620
 Ubuntu frames reconciliation as a collective effort,

861
00:52:17,620 --> 00:52:22,840
 with the entire community working to restore relationship.

862
00:52:22,840 --> 00:52:26,820
 In Sulha, the community representative

863
00:52:26,820 --> 00:52:30,460
 take on responsibility for managing the conflict,

864
00:52:30,460 --> 00:52:34,300
 shifting the burden away from the disputing parties.

865
00:52:34,300 --> 00:52:36,860
 These representative initiate, mediate,

866
00:52:36,860 --> 00:52:38,660
 and ensure the process,

867
00:52:38,660 --> 00:52:42,020
 helping victims and perpetrators restore dignity

868
00:52:42,020 --> 00:52:45,900
 and humanity while overcoming shame.

869
00:52:45,900 --> 00:52:48,740
 Gwanchi center on relational network

870
00:52:48,740 --> 00:52:52,520
 where community bonds are maintained through trust,

871
00:52:52,520 --> 00:52:55,500
 mutual obligation, and ongoing interaction,

872
00:52:55,500 --> 00:53:00,500
 creating harmony and strengthening connections over time.

873
00:53:00,500 --> 00:53:03,580
 And the last one,

874
00:53:03,580 --> 00:53:09,900
 the difference in its dialogue and relationship dynamics.

875
00:53:09,900 --> 00:53:14,820
 The four theologies offer different approaches to dialogue.

876
00:53:14,820 --> 00:53:17,740
 VOLF concept of differentiation

877
00:53:17,740 --> 00:53:21,600
 involve the self and the other negotiating identity

878
00:53:21,600 --> 00:53:23,620
 through mutual interaction,

879
00:53:23,620 --> 00:53:28,580
 balancing distinctiveness and unity.

880
00:53:28,580 --> 00:53:32,660
 Sulha process employ the Jaha community mediators

881
00:53:32,660 --> 00:53:36,420
 who serve as anger absorber to facilitate dialogue,

882
00:53:36,420 --> 00:53:39,620
 enabling parties to vent grievances

883
00:53:39,620 --> 00:53:42,620
 and move toward forgiveness and reconciliation.

884
00:53:42,620 --> 00:53:47,980
 Ubuntu emphasize the deep connection between people,

885
00:53:47,980 --> 00:53:52,300
 encouraging dialogue that foster a sense of community

886
00:53:52,300 --> 00:53:54,220
 and mutual understanding.

887
00:53:54,220 --> 00:53:58,180
 In this view, identity is shaped through recognizing the,

888
00:53:58,180 --> 00:54:01,260
 and respecting other within the community.

889
00:54:01,260 --> 00:54:03,700
 Gwanchi provide a framework for dialogue,

890
00:54:03,700 --> 00:54:07,140
 trust building, maintaining relational network,

891
00:54:07,140 --> 00:54:10,220
 preventing conflict, mediating tension,

892
00:54:10,220 --> 00:54:14,060
 which foster emotional bonds and balance relationship.

893
00:54:14,060 --> 00:54:21,300
 VOLF embrace Ubuntu, Sulha, and Gwanchi,

894
00:54:21,300 --> 00:54:23,460
 all value interconnectedness,

895
00:54:23,460 --> 00:54:26,340
 highlighting that true identity arise

896
00:54:26,340 --> 00:54:29,300
 from the relationships and communal belonging.

897
00:54:29,300 --> 00:54:35,260
 They see forgiveness as key to restoring harmony

898
00:54:35,260 --> 00:54:39,080
 and justice as important for right relation.

899
00:54:39,080 --> 00:54:41,780
 Despite their cultural differences,

900
00:54:41,780 --> 00:54:44,620
 these approaches share a focus on dialogue,

901
00:54:44,620 --> 00:54:48,260
 inclusivity, mutual respect, and rituals

902
00:54:48,260 --> 00:54:50,860
 that strengthen social cohesion and peace.

903
00:54:51,220 --> 00:54:53,460
 (coughing)

904
00:54:53,460 --> 00:54:58,380
 As peacemakers, Christians are called

905
00:54:58,380 --> 00:55:01,460
 to embody reconciliation, forgiveness,

906
00:55:01,460 --> 00:55:03,500
 and justice through their community.

907
00:55:03,500 --> 00:55:07,380
 Rooted in shared identity and mission,

908
00:55:07,380 --> 00:55:11,220
 the Christian community through its practices and rituals

909
00:55:11,220 --> 00:55:14,780
 becomes a space where faith is nurtured,

910
00:55:14,780 --> 00:55:17,980
 values are formed, and lives are transformed.

911
00:55:19,300 --> 00:55:21,780
 It is there that collective action,

912
00:55:21,780 --> 00:55:25,140
 guided by love and shaped by God's kingdom.

913
00:55:25,140 --> 00:55:28,660
 This foundation lead us to explore the deeper connection

914
00:55:28,660 --> 00:55:32,300
 between Christian community and its ritual,

915
00:55:32,300 --> 00:55:36,780
 mission, identity, and its transformative role in society.

916
00:55:36,780 --> 00:55:44,540
 I propose that to build peace and unity,

917
00:55:44,540 --> 00:55:49,020
 we need to strengthen our identity as peacemakers

918
00:55:49,020 --> 00:55:53,380
 through the Christian community and church practices.

919
00:55:53,380 --> 00:56:02,860
 Why Christian community?

920
00:56:02,860 --> 00:56:10,440
 Communities are shaped by shared beliefs

921
00:56:10,440 --> 00:56:12,400
 that drive collective action.

922
00:56:12,400 --> 00:56:16,780
 For religious communities, faith is not passive.

923
00:56:16,780 --> 00:56:19,420
 It is lived out in ways that build,

924
00:56:19,420 --> 00:56:21,620
 extend, and unite people.

925
00:56:21,620 --> 00:56:26,380
 When grounded in justice, compassion, and common good,

926
00:56:26,380 --> 00:56:29,440
 these communities become a force for creating

927
00:56:29,440 --> 00:56:33,260
 an inclusive and cooperative society.

928
00:56:33,260 --> 00:56:37,800
 In Christianity, God's mission is to bless all nations

929
00:56:37,800 --> 00:56:40,500
 through a community that embodies righteousness,

930
00:56:40,500 --> 00:56:43,840
 justice, peace, and transformation.

931
00:56:43,840 --> 00:56:48,800
 The identity, the values, the ethics,

932
00:56:48,800 --> 00:56:51,960
 and the social engagement of this community

933
00:56:51,960 --> 00:56:53,620
 are deeply intertwined.

934
00:56:53,620 --> 00:56:59,960
 The New Testament highlight several key elements

935
00:56:59,960 --> 00:57:06,300
 that characterize the Christian community first.

936
00:57:10,180 --> 00:57:14,180
 Matthew connect mission with identity.

937
00:57:14,180 --> 00:57:20,800
 He shows that Christian find their true identity

938
00:57:20,800 --> 00:57:25,060
 through mission, reflecting a new way of life

939
00:57:25,060 --> 00:57:28,980
 that demonstrate God's reality and offer salvation.

940
00:57:28,980 --> 00:57:32,820
 Christian community are different yet engaged,

941
00:57:32,820 --> 00:57:36,740
 presenting a life that is both appealing and challenging.

942
00:57:38,780 --> 00:57:43,660
 Luke, however, he presents the Christian community

943
00:57:43,660 --> 00:57:47,200
 as balancing inward and outward orientation.

944
00:57:47,200 --> 00:57:51,020
 Inwardly, shaping identity through teaching,

945
00:57:51,020 --> 00:57:53,820
 fellowship, breaking the bread, and prayer

946
00:57:53,820 --> 00:57:56,640
 for a shared sense of purpose and belonging.

947
00:57:56,640 --> 00:58:02,600
 Outwardly, he refuses to withdraw as a sectarian group,

948
00:58:02,600 --> 00:58:05,140
 but live as a redemptive presence,

949
00:58:05,140 --> 00:58:08,560
 reflect its identity in Christ and offering,

950
00:58:08,560 --> 00:58:12,020
 sorry.

951
00:58:12,020 --> 00:58:22,540
 Outwardly, refuse to withdraw as a sectarian group,

952
00:58:22,540 --> 00:58:24,940
 but live as a redemptive presence,

953
00:58:24,940 --> 00:58:26,940
 reflect its identity in Christ

954
00:58:26,940 --> 00:58:28,820
 and offering hope and renewal.

955
00:58:31,260 --> 00:58:35,820
 Third, reflecting values of God's kingdom.

956
00:58:35,820 --> 00:58:39,240
 For Paul, call the Christian community

957
00:58:39,240 --> 00:58:41,980
 to reflect the kingdom of values

958
00:58:41,980 --> 00:58:44,300
 and find their identity in Christ

959
00:58:44,300 --> 00:58:48,740
 rather than race, culture, class, or gender.

960
00:58:48,740 --> 00:58:51,040
 Unity becomes its defining mark,

961
00:58:51,040 --> 00:58:54,700
 demonstrated through love and peacemaking,

962
00:58:54,700 --> 00:58:56,260
 drawing others to God.

963
00:58:58,900 --> 00:59:01,820
 Paul also emphasized the church role

964
00:59:01,820 --> 00:59:03,900
 in God's redemptive work,

965
00:59:03,900 --> 00:59:08,660
 challenging oppression and living out the great commission,

966
00:59:08,660 --> 00:59:11,940
 the proclamation of gospel, and the great commandment,

967
00:59:11,940 --> 00:59:14,180
 the loving and serving others.

968
00:59:14,180 --> 00:59:15,420
 This identity,

969
00:59:15,420 --> 00:59:20,660
 commented to justice, love, and service,

970
00:59:20,660 --> 00:59:24,300
 transform lives, priorities, and values,

971
00:59:24,300 --> 00:59:27,560
 becoming a sign of God's new creation.

972
00:59:28,560 --> 00:59:32,840
 And lastly, for Paul,

973
00:59:32,840 --> 00:59:37,800
 he highlights that suffering is essential to God's mission.

974
00:59:37,800 --> 00:59:42,720
 Enduring hardship shapes the community's identity in Christ

975
00:59:42,720 --> 00:59:45,760
 and demonstrate its commitment to redemptive,

976
00:59:45,760 --> 00:59:49,000
 mirroring Christ's sacrificial love and hope.

977
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:51,520
 In this way, the Christian community

978
00:59:51,520 --> 00:59:54,780
 lives out its identity and mission.

979
00:59:54,780 --> 00:59:57,540
 (pages rustling)

980
00:59:57,540 --> 01:00:01,620
 And why church practices?

981
01:00:01,620 --> 01:00:02,840
 Why liturgy?

982
01:00:02,840 --> 01:00:09,220
 Rituals are symbolic action,

983
01:00:09,220 --> 01:00:12,980
 or ceremonies rooted in tradition and purpose,

984
01:00:12,980 --> 01:00:16,100
 connecting us to personal and communal stories,

985
01:00:16,100 --> 01:00:20,700
 expressing shared belief and strengthening bonds.

986
01:00:20,700 --> 01:00:24,760
 Rituals provide structure to guide emotion and thoughts,

987
01:00:24,760 --> 01:00:27,780
 reshaping memories, attitude, and desires

988
01:00:27,780 --> 01:00:31,880
 toward values like truth, repentance, and forgiveness.

989
01:00:31,880 --> 01:00:34,700
 Rituals

990
01:00:34,700 --> 01:00:41,100
 shape individual and communities

991
01:00:41,100 --> 01:00:43,700
 as agent of peace in three meaningful ways.

992
01:00:43,700 --> 01:00:45,700
 First, rituals

993
01:00:45,700 --> 01:00:52,100
 shape identity and collective values.

994
01:00:52,100 --> 01:00:54,060
 Church practices such as fellowship,

995
01:00:54,060 --> 01:00:55,960
 teaching, and Lord's Supper,

996
01:00:55,960 --> 01:00:58,840
 food washing, singing, and shared meals

997
01:00:58,840 --> 01:01:02,900
 create space for the Holy Spirit to transform us.

998
01:01:02,900 --> 01:01:09,100
 These practices renew our covenant with God,

999
01:01:09,100 --> 01:01:11,240
 deepen our identity in Christ,

1000
01:01:11,240 --> 01:01:15,020
 and nurture accountability in walking with his path.

1001
01:01:15,020 --> 01:01:19,020
 Second, rituals unite and transform us.

1002
01:01:20,420 --> 01:01:23,300
 Repeated participation in practices

1003
01:01:23,300 --> 01:01:25,220
 like communion or food washing

1004
01:01:25,220 --> 01:01:31,340
 values such forgiveness, justice, and reconciliation

1005
01:01:31,340 --> 01:01:34,400
 become woven into the fabric of communal life.

1006
01:01:34,400 --> 01:01:38,220
 These actions go beyond symbolism,

1007
01:01:38,220 --> 01:01:41,460
 forming habits that shape individual's character

1008
01:01:41,460 --> 01:01:43,580
 and collective identity.

1009
01:01:43,580 --> 01:01:48,580
 And the third task is rituals challenge cultural norms

1010
01:01:49,300 --> 01:01:50,980
 and inspire change.

1011
01:01:50,980 --> 01:01:54,140
 Since we are not only product of our culture,

1012
01:01:54,140 --> 01:01:56,340
 but producers of our culture,

1013
01:01:56,340 --> 01:01:59,140
 we have the power to reshape it

1014
01:01:59,140 --> 01:02:02,540
 by addressing broader societal challenges.

1015
01:02:02,540 --> 01:02:06,660
 Church practices models values of love, truth, unity,

1016
01:02:06,660 --> 01:02:10,100
 and peace counter dominant societal patterns

1017
01:02:10,100 --> 01:02:13,100
 of hatred, division, and exclusion.

1018
01:02:13,100 --> 01:02:14,460
 Embedding these values,

1019
01:02:14,460 --> 01:02:17,840
 the church become a living witness to God's kingdom.

1020
01:02:18,900 --> 01:02:22,220
 Church rituals connect us to the mystery of God's

1021
01:02:22,220 --> 01:02:25,520
 fostering a sense of belonging and deepening fear.

1022
01:02:25,520 --> 01:02:30,060
 In this communal space, unity grows.

1023
01:02:30,060 --> 01:02:34,100
 We learn to walk in harmony with God and one another,

1024
01:02:34,100 --> 01:02:36,520
 and embrace peace as a way of life.

1025
01:02:36,520 --> 01:02:43,420
 One example, this one I found in African church.

1026
01:02:43,420 --> 01:02:46,580
 This is fascinating.

1027
01:02:46,580 --> 01:02:51,020
 On Saturday evening, the church gather

1028
01:02:51,020 --> 01:02:54,040
 for love feast prayer, they call it,

1029
01:02:54,040 --> 01:02:57,440
 as preparation for communal for the next day, for Sunday.

1030
01:02:57,440 --> 01:03:03,100
 So they use this as a ritual before the communion on Sunday.

1031
01:03:03,100 --> 01:03:06,900
 Water symbolize the purity and transparency of love

1032
01:03:06,900 --> 01:03:09,060
 within the community,

1033
01:03:09,060 --> 01:03:11,460
 encouraging members to reconcile

1034
01:03:11,460 --> 01:03:14,420
 and mend broken relationship before communion.

1035
01:03:16,120 --> 01:03:18,340
 Participants drink the water together.

1036
01:03:18,340 --> 01:03:20,620
 So everyone has his own cup of water.

1037
01:03:20,620 --> 01:03:22,860
 If I feel good around everyone,

1038
01:03:22,860 --> 01:03:27,860
 I don't have issues or tension, I drink the water.

1039
01:03:27,860 --> 01:03:31,940
 If so, I will go to the person and just maybe reconcile

1040
01:03:31,940 --> 01:03:33,200
 and then drink the water.

1041
01:03:33,200 --> 01:03:39,180
 This is amazing ritual, I think.

1042
01:03:39,180 --> 01:03:43,260
 It encourage us every week to test our relationship

1043
01:03:43,260 --> 01:03:44,660
 within the church.

1044
01:03:45,500 --> 01:03:47,320
 (audience laughing)

1045
01:03:47,320 --> 01:03:52,320
 Bread represents oneness and fellowship.

1046
01:03:52,320 --> 01:03:57,560
 Each person shares their piece of bread within the other,

1047
01:03:57,560 --> 01:04:00,600
 filling their cups with shared pieces

1048
01:04:00,600 --> 01:04:03,280
 as a gesture of unity and love.

1049
01:04:03,280 --> 01:04:04,880
 So each one will go to the other,

1050
01:04:04,880 --> 01:04:09,520
 will have take a piece of bread and give a piece of bread.

1051
01:04:10,920 --> 01:04:15,920
 And then the service concludes with a bread placed

1052
01:04:15,920 --> 01:04:19,800
 on the altar and the congregation sing Amazing Grace.

1053
01:04:19,800 --> 01:04:26,300
 So this is kind of ritual that transform us weekly.

1054
01:04:26,300 --> 01:04:28,120
 Let's put it this way.

1055
01:04:28,120 --> 01:04:33,500
 So what are the learning outcome?

1056
01:04:33,500 --> 01:04:38,700
 Christian theology can glean valuable insights

1057
01:04:38,700 --> 01:04:41,140
 from Ubuntu, Sulha, and Gwanshi.

1058
01:04:41,140 --> 01:04:44,940
 First, peace and unity are communal responsibility.

1059
01:04:44,940 --> 01:04:53,380
 Ubuntu and Sulha show how communal support and solidarity

1060
01:04:53,380 --> 01:04:57,220
 are essential for facilitating reconciliation.

1061
01:04:57,220 --> 01:04:59,980
 Unlike many Western reconciliation theology,

1062
01:04:59,980 --> 01:05:04,980
 which focus on the triangle of offender, offended, and God,

1063
01:05:06,440 --> 01:05:10,520
 in these approaches, it includes the community as well,

1064
01:05:10,520 --> 01:05:16,880
 forming a broader shared process of restoration.

1065
01:05:16,880 --> 01:05:24,080
 This insight enrich Christian theology

1066
01:05:24,080 --> 01:05:26,040
 regarding the community's role

1067
01:05:26,040 --> 01:05:29,160
 in healing individuals and relationships.

1068
01:05:29,160 --> 01:05:34,460
 By prioritizing communal well-being,

1069
01:05:34,460 --> 01:05:36,960
 as seen in Ubuntu, Sulha, and Gwanshi,

1070
01:05:36,960 --> 01:05:40,600
 Christian community can become spaces

1071
01:05:40,600 --> 01:05:43,600
 where forgiveness, justice, and unity

1072
01:05:43,600 --> 01:05:46,080
 are not just personal virtues,

1073
01:05:46,080 --> 01:05:49,080
 but shared values and responsibilities,

1074
01:05:49,080 --> 01:05:53,200
 enabling healing and reconciliation through collective care.

1075
01:05:53,200 --> 01:06:01,160
 Second, ritualizing peace processes

1076
01:06:01,160 --> 01:06:02,960
 can facilitate reconciliation.

1077
01:06:03,840 --> 01:06:08,460
 Sulha ceremonies element, or Sulha ceremonial elements,

1078
01:06:08,460 --> 01:06:11,260
 provide a meaningful framework for healing.

1079
01:06:11,260 --> 01:06:14,100
 By gradually ritualizing forgiveness,

1080
01:06:14,100 --> 01:06:16,060
 repentance, and reparation,

1081
01:06:16,060 --> 01:06:19,420
 Sulha highlights the importance of public witnessing

1082
01:06:19,420 --> 01:06:21,880
 and shared reconciliation.

1083
01:06:21,880 --> 01:06:24,400
 Christian theology can incorporate

1084
01:06:24,400 --> 01:06:27,340
 similar rituals into communal life.

1085
01:06:27,340 --> 01:06:29,500
 Public expressions of forgiveness,

1086
01:06:29,500 --> 01:06:32,980
 acknowledging the pain, lamentation,

1087
01:06:32,980 --> 01:06:35,180
 and restoration of dignity

1088
01:06:35,180 --> 01:06:37,540
 can make reconciliation more tangible

1089
01:06:37,540 --> 01:06:41,060
 and accessible for all involved,

1090
01:06:41,060 --> 01:06:44,880
 strengthening the bonds of interconnectedness and unity.

1091
01:06:44,880 --> 01:06:50,180
 And third, ongoing relationship building

1092
01:06:50,180 --> 01:06:52,260
 is essential for communal harmony.

1093
01:06:52,260 --> 01:06:56,840
 Gwanshi offers a relational framework

1094
01:06:56,840 --> 01:07:00,620
 that focus on trust, reciprocity, and social dignity

1095
01:07:00,620 --> 01:07:05,380
 achieved through informal practices and daily rituals.

1096
01:07:05,380 --> 01:07:07,780
 Gwanshi remind Christian theology

1097
01:07:07,780 --> 01:07:09,460
 of the importance of

1098
01:07:09,460 --> 01:07:16,400
 ongoing relationship building for reconciliation.

1099
01:07:16,400 --> 01:07:22,060
 Practices like mutual support, respect, and hospitality

1100
01:07:22,060 --> 01:07:25,140
 demonstrate how small, consistent act

1101
01:07:25,140 --> 01:07:28,060
 foster relationship and mediate tension,

1102
01:07:28,060 --> 01:07:31,220
 aligning with Christian practices like sharing meal,

1103
01:07:31,220 --> 01:07:34,220
 offering forgiveness, and communal prayer.

1104
01:07:34,220 --> 01:07:36,540
 By balancing individual obligation

1105
01:07:36,540 --> 01:07:38,540
 within communal well-being,

1106
01:07:38,540 --> 01:07:40,940
 Gwanshi challenges Christian community

1107
01:07:40,940 --> 01:07:44,240
 to view reconciliation not as an event,

1108
01:07:44,240 --> 01:07:47,060
 but as a way of life grounded in trust,

1109
01:07:47,060 --> 01:07:49,160
 respect, and shared responsibility.

1110
01:07:49,160 --> 01:07:56,480
 So I want to end this presentation

1111
01:07:56,480 --> 01:08:01,420
 with relating identity to my personal life and context.

1112
01:08:01,420 --> 01:08:06,700
 As a Palestinian with an Israeli citizenship,

1113
01:08:06,700 --> 01:08:10,160
 my identity has always been conflicted.

1114
01:08:10,160 --> 01:08:15,300
 A space where two opposing reality coexist,

1115
01:08:15,300 --> 01:08:18,940
 and as long as the Palestinian-Israeli conflict is ongoing,

1116
01:08:18,940 --> 01:08:22,500
 this conflicted within us continue

1117
01:08:24,000 --> 01:08:26,920
 to cause and incomfortable.

1118
01:08:26,920 --> 01:08:32,100
 For many, I am included.

1119
01:08:32,100 --> 01:08:35,780
 This is described as an identity crisis, actually,

1120
01:08:35,780 --> 01:08:38,060
 but God led me through a process

1121
01:08:38,060 --> 01:08:39,860
 where this identity crisis

1122
01:08:39,860 --> 01:08:42,260
 shaped how I understand my calling.

1123
01:08:42,260 --> 01:08:48,220
 This unique tension pushed me to wrestle

1124
01:08:48,220 --> 01:08:52,660
 with the meaning of identity in a world torn by conflict.

1125
01:08:53,660 --> 01:08:57,840
 I've come to see that our identities are not static.

1126
01:08:57,840 --> 01:09:02,000
 They are stories we live out,

1127
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:04,580
 shaped by our relationships with others.

1128
01:09:04,580 --> 01:09:09,100
 God used this internal struggle to reveal to me

1129
01:09:09,100 --> 01:09:12,120
 the mystery of living in the in-between,

1130
01:09:12,120 --> 01:09:16,960
 a space of reconciliation, not avoidance.

1131
01:09:18,880 --> 01:09:22,980
 This revelation illuminates my calling as a bridge builder

1132
01:09:22,980 --> 01:09:27,780
 between two worlds often defined by mutual exclusion.

1133
01:09:27,780 --> 01:09:31,620
 Living in the in-between is not a weakness,

1134
01:09:31,620 --> 01:09:36,380
 but a divine opportunity to embody Christ's reconciling love,

1135
01:09:36,380 --> 01:09:38,700
 drawing on the strength of both,

1136
01:09:38,700 --> 01:09:41,740
 being Palestinian and Israeli at the same time,

1137
01:09:41,740 --> 01:09:44,940
 while resisting the temptation of dehumanizing the other.

1138
01:09:44,940 --> 01:09:48,340
 This is on the personal level,

1139
01:09:48,340 --> 01:09:50,460
 but on the broader level,

1140
01:09:50,460 --> 01:09:52,860
 the ongoing struggle in Israel-Palestine,

1141
01:09:52,860 --> 01:09:54,440
 or in Palestine-Israel,

1142
01:09:54,440 --> 01:10:02,700
 demonstrates the destructive power of exclusion.

1143
01:10:02,700 --> 01:10:06,120
 When one group define its identity

1144
01:10:06,120 --> 01:10:08,700
 as pure without the other,

1145
01:10:08,700 --> 01:10:12,100
 and its perspective as entirely righteous,

1146
01:10:13,100 --> 01:10:17,500
 it often group, sorry,

1147
01:10:17,500 --> 01:10:23,580
 it often cast the other as corrupt, guilty, or unworthy.

1148
01:10:23,580 --> 01:10:26,940
 This binary thinking dehumanize

1149
01:10:26,940 --> 01:10:30,140
 and fuel the cycle of violence.

1150
01:10:30,140 --> 01:10:34,580
 But what if we embrace a different vision of identity,

1151
01:10:34,580 --> 01:10:38,580
 one that acknowledge the complexity of the interdependence?

1152
01:10:38,580 --> 01:10:42,700
 Paris Love Wolf's concept of embrace speak directly to this.

1153
01:10:42,700 --> 01:10:46,340
 True peace arise not from erasing differences,

1154
01:10:46,340 --> 01:10:49,300
 but from creating space for the other,

1155
01:10:49,300 --> 01:10:53,040
 while maintaining our own identity.

1156
01:10:53,040 --> 01:10:56,460
 I believe the future of Israel-Palestine

1157
01:10:56,460 --> 01:10:59,820
 from the identity cultural perspective

1158
01:10:59,820 --> 01:11:04,820
 depends on how both sides handle this delicate balance.

1159
01:11:05,640 --> 01:11:08,680
 For us as Palestinian with Israeli citizenship,

1160
01:11:08,680 --> 01:11:12,320
 this means confronting our own tendencies toward exclusion

1161
01:11:12,320 --> 01:11:13,840
 while challenging others,

1162
01:11:13,840 --> 01:11:19,100
 which in this case is the powerful party, to do the same.

1163
01:11:19,100 --> 01:11:23,360
 It's about being rooted in justice and truth,

1164
01:11:23,360 --> 01:11:26,640
 yet open to the possibility of reconciliation.

1165
01:11:26,640 --> 01:11:29,560
 My identity as Palestinian and Israeli

1166
01:11:29,560 --> 01:11:32,800
 is a daily reminder that bridges can be built,

1167
01:11:32,800 --> 01:11:37,800
 even between worlds that seem irreconciled.

1168
01:11:37,800 --> 01:11:40,400
 Thank you.

1169
01:11:40,400 --> 01:11:43,560
 (audience applauding)

1170
01:11:43,560 --> 01:11:47,580
 (upbeat music)

1171
01:11:47,580 --> 01:11:50,160
 (upbeat music)

1172
01:11:50,160 --> 01:11:52,740
 (upbeat music)

1173
01:11:52,740 --> 01:11:55,320
 (upbeat music)

